segments.text: Would you explain how you acquired your early interest in oceanography and your early academic training?
Yeah, my early academic training was as an undergraduate in physics.
The war came along, and I was teaching V-12 Navy students mathematics.
I was also interested in graduate school in astronomy, and so I had a navigation course to teach.
Now, where was this?
Yeah, and the navigation course kind of got me interested in oceanography.
I think that's basically it.
Well, the first time I come in contact with your career, you were at Scripps.
No, I was never at Scripps.
You didn't go to Scripps and worked him in 40?
No, I was in Scripps for the summer of 1949 once.
Before that, I don't think I ever was at Scripps.
My impression was that you appeared there briefly in 40.
I suppose I got that from Roger Revelle.
I think he's wrong.
In 40, I don't think I...
I certainly had never heard of oceanography before.
I thought it was chemistry or something like that.

And then I was looking around for something a little bit more active to do, and Lyman Spitzer, who was the professor of astrophysics at Yale, whom I'd known before Pearl Harbor, had gone to work in underwater sound work, and so he suggested I might come to Woods Hole.

and that was 1944, and he, because I had already got this interest in navigation and so forth, it was quite an interesting opportunity for me to come to its own, see something firsthand about ships and work at sea and so forth.
That was first working in a project for Morris Ewing,
on the shallow thermoclines and the acoustic tracking on the upper layers.
And I don't think I made out too well in that because the viewing somehow didn't communicate very well what it was he was doing.
He was terribly busy.
And after about six months of that, I think it was something like that, I started to work with Alan Vaughn, for Alan Vaughn.
on constructing some new kinds of repeating smoke glass, battery thermo-grass.
And I was working for him probably for a total of two years, something like that.
and then started to work for Jeffries Wyman, who was a physiologist from Harvard who was working here on clouds, cumulus clouds.
I think until I met Wyman, I had no idea about a scientific paper or how to really do any scientific research.
Before that, it was being a technical assistant.

And it was working with Wyman that gave me some idea about how you ask questions, and how you formulate models, and something about the scientific literature, which I didn't have any idea about before at all.
That probably worked more or less in Wyman's projects up until 1947, probably.
No, but when you were working with thermoclimes, you were working with any submarine warfare, is that right?
Well, yes, that's what it was.
For that first half year or a year, I guess, altogether, if you include the bath and thermograph stuff, maybe a year and a half.
Then the world was over, and most of the people who were here
A large number of them decided, I think, that there was really very little professional future in oceanography, and they all disappeared.
Some went back to universities to teach basic subjects, and others went down to Navy laboratories in southern Spain, but only a very few stayed here, by comparison.
I think 1949, 1950 was a low point in the population of the Asian Graffiti Institution.
When did you first become interested in waves, though?
Well, I guess I've never been interested in, very much, in surface waves.
I was interested, the work I did that had anything to do with waves was very low frequency, raspy waves in the ocean.
That was probably, I don't know, I think that was about 1955, 57, something like that.

And, but as far as surface waves are concerned, or internal waves, high frequency stuff, I really, I don't think I've ever written any paper at all, except one, a retracted paper that I wrote for a Russian journal called Duklady, 1950, I think it was.
And after I discovered that the
The paper had been, the material in the paper had really been worked out much earlier by Osmond Reynolds.
I wrote a, sent a telegram to them asking them to either just to withdraw the paper or to, to destroy it.
So it was a long period, then finally a telegram came from Mackey Radio, which said, which the secretary of the institution brought in rather tremblingly and said,
Mr. Stommel, per your instructions, the papers have been destroyed.
Krylov and Boguglia, something like that.
Moscow.
That was just the time of the McCarthy hearings and so forth, so we were kind of a little bit scared what was going to happen, but evidently it slipped through the CIA and FBI net.
Never heard anything about it.
They probably still have a file.
I don't know.
I think that they're not very efficient.
I don't think they ever picked that one up.
It never came up on any kind of...
clearance or anything like that over the many years.
What was Woods Hole like in those early years?
Well, it was confined to that one building.
When I first came here, there were German prisoners of war cleaning up after the 1944 hurricane.
And both of our ships, which were kind of small ships, the original Lattice and the
Saluda, I think it was, were up the ground on Ram Island.
And we pulled off.
And everything was in that one building.
There was quite a few small buildings on the docks.
The heavy emphasis on explosive work, testing of different kinds of charges against model submarine hulls, that was a big problem.
Because the Navy 7 was gone.
And then there was the smaller acoustic program, which Ewing was carrying out mostly.
And there were some biological programs about anti-fouling paint and about trying to reduce foam and see nine tubes in the wakes of landing craft when they were visible, things like that.
where they got great big suitcases full of blue ration stamps to buy meat and all.
It was a very different place than it is now.
People were, although it was a very intense, dedicated activity in connection with war effort, and people were working there.
long hours on the weekends and so forth, and I think there was an exceptionally high morale at the place at that time.
The feeling of having to accomplish something every day.
I think basically the level of industry perhaps twice what it is today.
If you walk around in the relaxed atmosphere of our laboratory today, compared to the intense activity at that time, it was much, much harder work going on.
Of course, we didn't have any large ships like the Atlantis, so we left the Atlantis too.
Everything was reasonably uncomfortable on those little boats.
Testing, one, two, three, testing.
Testing, one, two, three, testing.
Yeah.
We were picking up some static someplace or what have you, but that's a lot better.
How large was Woods Hole, Woods Hole roughly in terms of faculty then, I suppose?
Well, is it on?
Yes, on.
When I, just after the people, just after the wartime when people had left, it was probably, it was probably very small.
I don't know the number, but
probably the total number of people was less than a hundred.
And there were no, there was no tenure appointments or anything like that.
There were a few people, maybe two or three, who had been granted some kind of long-term contract, but everybody else lived hand-to-mouth.
The contracts, the grants were negotiated almost entirely by the director himself, so we didn't have to write proposals all the time.
And we felt fairly, we felt reasonably secure, but being 25, 28 or something like that, it's not a big concern if you're not married.
And it was still operating very much in the style of a
of a summer vacation laboratory with an increase of population in the summer of maybe doubled, something of that sort.
So I would guess around 100, but maybe that's wrong and most of those people really, no retirement idea or any kind of commitment of any part of the institution at all.
That took maybe eight or ten years to begin to take place.

Now, people at Scripps seemed to think that there was more exchange among the faculty, more, dealt with wider varieties of ideas rather than a limited academic field in the 40s and the early 50s because of the closeness of the faculty, the size of the faculty.
Was that your impression here at Woods Hole?
You mean that there was more interchange between different physicists?
Right.
Biologists talked more to physicists who talked more to mathematicians or whatever.
Oh, I think that's true.
I think there was all being in one building and having a common tea in the afternoon.
Always a lot of people from, there was only one tea.
You go around a place like this, I suppose there must be 40 coffee pots in this institution today.
I suppose, well, the coffee pots weren't running all day long, and there was one teapot in the afternoon.
And that, I think, made people talk to each other about all that.
And then there were lots of interdisciplinary cruises.
ship time is a lot tighter than fewer ships, so people got accustomed to each other's work that way.

I think the textbook by Spheredip Johnson and Fleming is rather indicative of the way that all the different aspects of oceanography are kind of lumped together in one curriculum or one group of people.
I know.
In my first days here, you see, in my first days, when it was just beginning, I had a smattering of work at Sea and Acoustics and instrumentability.
I don't really match, but I had an expeditionary work in meteorology.
And I worked for a little while, for a short time, with a biologist on, Gordon Riley, on plankton models.

So I had an opportunity to play with meteorology, some elementary chemistry, and plankton ideas, and several aspects of oceanography, both in the field and theoretical sort of things, all in those first few years.
But I think probably
My fields of interest have narrowed quite a bit since that time.
I don't do anything meteorology or biology.
It's partly the nature of the field, but it's also partly living in next door offices with people working in other disciplines.
This whole side of the building, for example, is all people connected with current meters, one way or another.
I had to go upstairs to a chemist or down to the other laboratory to see instruments or ships.
I don't even see ships out there.
That's a noticeable change.
Do you feel the stanalgia concerning the time when most oceanographers were journalists?
No, I don't.
I think the nature of science is much better now.
I think science was very exploratory and thin.
If you look at Sredip's book, you get an idea how thin it is.

I think one has a nostalgia for any kind of thing to happen in the past, but it's not very strong in me, and I think that the sense of excitement and so forth is right now, this feeling that the science has developed into something interesting, something intricate enough that makes it interesting to people in other fields.
We actually have

in physical oceanography now a pretty good connection with people in hydrodynamics and fluid mechanical people, even to some degree with astrophysicists and astronomers, people who are interested in fluids on a large scale other than the Earth, and very good relations with meteorologists, more than we had before.
The subject, the theoretical knowledge of the subject, the theoretical body of knowledge of the subject has grown tremendously from what it was in the 40s.
There weren't any models, there weren't any ideas of how the ocean circulation went at that time, at least with the very rare exception of the Ekrem's model.
which sat around sort of untouched for something like 50 years.
Heckman wrote his spiral paper, I think in 1902 or maybe a little bit earlier.
Publications in about 1902.
He didn't actually go out and try to make any observations on it.
He wrote some very interesting papers in between that are not very useful today.
He didn't go out to look for it until 1932.
And he didn't publish the results until 1954.
He died in 1956.
So, I think that's about the approximate dates.
So, 52 years went between the time he wrote his theoretical paper and the time he wrote his analysis of an experimental results of the attempt to measure the spiral.
The results weren't very good.
I don't think the field could wait so long.
It's amazing.

in terms of grant getting in the late 40s and the early 50s, it seemed almost as if institutions received sort of block grants, particularly here at Lamont and Scripps, and sort of divided them up among the various researchers.
Yeah, I think it wasn't really, yes, in effect it was like block grants, but it was grants to directors, people who had established a

There were very, very few people established in the government's eyes as competition actors, and these people were people like Smith and Ravel and Hisler and Ewing, and so they made the major, they, it was,
You could imagine a German institution where there's a chief professor who gets all the money and then hands it out and tells people what to do.
Well, that's sort of the way it was here.
The Islan got all the money and he handed it out.
He never asked you to submit an estimated budget or anything like that.
He did all of that.
If you needed some money, you'd go and ask them, and generally it was worth coming.
Ship time, the same way.
You never knew whether you were going to have a ship or not.
Someday, the whole ship scheduling procedure was in his head, and then he would come and say, you know, the advantage will be available for a month or two weeks from today.
and we'd want to take her out, and that's the kind of preparation you would have on a cruise.
Of course, you knew that that might happen, so you were a little bit prepared.
But it was like that, largely through one person, the director.
The institution was small, so it worked quite well, almost like a project leader or something.
And, of course, he was an exceptionally nice man, and so it worked very well without any kinds of friction or unhappiness.
People who were too big to live with a system like that, like Ewing, they just had to go start another laboratory somewhere else.
They couldn't take it that way, that kind of patronage, and then they had to go somewhere else, and they did.
They started off their own outfits quite nicely.
The number of laboratories in this period seemed to increase by leaps and bounds, with Scripps and Woods Hole, of course, you know, leading the way.
But, gee, Washington, Oregon State almost begins a few years later.
Yes, but I think the, I don't, I don't, that's interesting.
I don't know that the number of institutions grew very fast.
I don't, it'd be interesting to know what the, how it went, but I think that they probably

There was a famous, well, after the war, several years went by and oceanography was kind of a low end, and then in the National Academy of Sciences there was a report put together, I think mostly under Harrison Brown, perhaps it was an earlier one, and this had the
This woke a lot of people.
This broke loose some money.
A lot of places started to, at that time, began to start to set up institutions.
Seattle had been going for a long time, probably before Woods Hole, on a very small basis.
But
I think places, I don't know, I think places like Texas A&M and Oregon State and University of Miami and so forth really sort of began to start in the mid-50s, I think.
I don't believe earlier than that.
I think that's right.
I think so.
And I think it was part and parcel of that initiative which the Academy had taken in trying to make this field more visible.
I think it was the mid-50s.
And then the big flux of students began in the early 60s, mid-60s.
That's when the students, when the educational programs began to get set up.
good students began to appear in the early 60s, but a whole new generation began to appear as a result of all these different places where they set up their educational institutions.
That's when the new PhDs began to appear, but very few in 59 and 60.
There was a noticeable low period, I think, from 1948 to 1955, 56,
This would be roughly in the period when the ONR was your major funder.
Yes, it was.
They kept the whole thing alive for a long time.
Did it seem to you they were more interested then in research and development than mission orientation?
Oh, yeah, they were much more.
The ONR was extremely generous about letting you do more or less anything you wanted to do.
It would be called military oceanography, but it wasn't military oceanography.
It could be tracking the Gulf Stream or
tracking surface loads drifting around.
Just listening.
ONR never really asked if there was any need to justify things on the basis of social needs or military needs.
That never filtered down, as far as I know, in that period, 1948 to 1950s.
It never filtered down to the individual investigators.
Maybe the directors had to cut some lines, but the individual investigators never had to.
So you didn't seem to have any problem having your projects funded?
No, of course we were satisfied with very modest funding.
We're happy to have them.
happy to have salaries of around $3,000 a year.
And if we had a budget, if we were going to buy some equipment and so forth, and the budget came for something like $20,000 over a year, it couldn't be regarded as a very big thing.
So I'd rather have it long.
How large was the first grant you received?
That's a good question.
I got grant money from ISM.
When did I try to, when did I first try to stand on my own feet and write a grant?
That's an interesting question.
Probably, probably around 1951 or 1952, I got some grant from
There were two grants.
One was from the Atomic Energy Commission for internal wave monitoring thing off the river.
The other was from a special code in ONR, which I don't remember what the name of the code ONR was, Naval Research Code, for
making some studies of the infrared noise from the C-cells.
And those two things basically, I guess, eventually led to the establishment of the Panularis station data at Bermuda.
That was the material wave that led to that.
going to lead to internal waste because we found that, oh, I remember, we told the AEC we were going to make pressure measurements on the slope of the river.
It turned out that we were unable to do that, so we made temperature measurements instead, and then wrote out those results as internal weight measurements.
We really didn't use all the cable they gave us.

But the, and then that eventually led to the Panoleros stations at Bermuda, but the infrared thing began to be quite a burden and so we asked, we found Bill Richardson who was working at the Patel Institute or something like that to come and take that project over.
And for some years we were flying infrared detectors around the Gulf, over the Gulf Stream.
It never became a very
a very useful tool for industrial studies, but it was the one we tried to make work.

I guess 1951, 1952, those were probably the first distinct projects that I got separate from working under the resistance programs, because I know certainly in 1953 and 1954, I was trying to do some other work under the Morani resistance program.

Of course, I suppose really the time that I would know, the time that I would actually know I was writing my own proposals was certainly when I started over at Harvard in 1960, then, because then there wasn't any sheltering in the internal environment.
And it was probably before that.
But you're a relatively well-known oceanographer by 1951.
Well, yeah, but it was a very small field and I didn't have any great urge to build an empire or to get out from under Islam or anything like that.
It was quite a comfortable, nice setup for me.
I'd forgotten when he gave up being the director and Admiral Smith came in.
But his was still around and still, I think, understood the military oceanography program for quite some time.
When did you first meet Walter Munk?
Well, that's an interesting question.
I might have met him before 1949, but I think I met him during the summer of 1949 is when I first met him.

I went out to Scripps, and I had just done my little Gulf Stream model, I mean ocean model, and I met him out there, and we talked about that, and then I think he went that fall, it was the fall of 49, to Norway, Bergen, for a sabbatical or something.
And that's funny, he did his 1950 paper.
And then of course there was a long period when I didn't know him very well.
He wanted us to get out of oceanography for a period then.
I don't know exactly when, probably about 1953, 1968 or 65.
It was a period of maybe a little over 10 years when he worked primarily on geophysical problems.
Not Oceans.
So then, actually, I wasn't really following very much what he was doing there.
Then we went to... Then, of course, I saw him again in 1959 when we were there for the spring one time.
We haven't ever done, never really did it very much together.
We did, I think maybe this one paper that he and, Walter and I and Horowitz wrote on internal weight measurements.
I don't remember the date of that.
Probably 1956, 1955.
The question was rather, by the way, an unfair one for this reason, is because he says that by the 50s, he thinks you're doing the most important work in oceanography being done.
How would you answer that?
Well, that's very nice of him.
Of course, he was not working in the field, so I didn't have any competition.
But I don't think that's perhaps...
I don't think that's...
Well, I mean, the point is that there's very little being done.
And I think that's the real answer.
Okay.
So, but, you know, the point is that then, you know, by 51 or 52, then, you know, clearly you've established yourself in this particular discipline as the leader.
And so I'm a little surprised about the way the grants are operating then between 52 and 60.
Yeah, but, I mean, that's a personality problem.
If you have a...
a nice comfortable arrangement in a laboratory where the director's a nice guy and you can it's very easy to argue
